$ SQL server - date datatype


{ Date literals

  { cast as datetime #mssql-cast-as-datetime

    When a string is cast as `datetime`, the current language is considered. The following cast would not work if the language was set to `german`, for example.

code {
→ development/databases/SQL-Server/T-SQL/statements/set#mssql-set-language[set language] english
select
  cast('2018-08-28' as datetime)
code }

  }
}
{ functions

  `getdate()` returns a *datetime* datatype (whose precision is about 3 to 4 milliseconds) while `sysdatetime()` returns a *datetime2(7)* datatype (whose precision is
  in the nano seconds).
  -
  `sysdatetime` should be preferred over `getdate()`.

  `datepart` can be used to extract parts of a date, for example
code {
→ development/databases/SQL-Server/sql/select[select] datepart(hour, sysdatetime());
code }

}
{ date arithmetic

  → development/databases/SQL-Server/T-SQL/functions#t-sql-dateadd[`dateadd`]

